			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I would agree that the target should not know who is hunting him, until he is attacked.  When a target is in a zone, they should be able to determine that there are hunters in the same area but not be able to determine which hunters or if that hunter is even after them.
<br />

<br />
The first time the bounty hunter encounters the target they should have the upper hand.  The target should not be able to attack the hunter until this initial encounter where the hunter reveals himself.  
<br />

<br />
Weapon choice should have some ability to cloak who the attacker is.  If a bounty hunter chooses a long range weapon the ability to determine the attacker's identity should be diminished.  If a bounty hunter chooses a short range blaster or poisonous insect then the target should be able to identify the hunter.
<br />

<br />
After the initial encounter, the target should have some ability to determine if a hunter is close.  The hunter should have some ability to determine the direction a target flees.  If the target "gates" to another area...the hunter should be able to develop the skill of determining which direction they headed.  <img src="images/smiles/icon_biggrin.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
