			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I tend to agree with the theory of allowing the hunted to attack the hunter without prior engagement. The hunted shouldn't know who's hunting them but should know the generality that a bounty has been placed on their head. I liked the idea of using slicers to hack and find a bounty's information and thereby finding out the hunter(s)'s identity.
<br />

<br />
Throughout Star Wars literature there's examples of bounty hunters competing over a kill. By providing this feeling of competition the hunter would have to make the decision to either wait until the best possible time or to grab his kill before another finds the poor chap.
<br />

<br />
One problem that may come up is the obvious question of who can defend the hunted from the bounty hunter. The encounter can't be just between the hunter and the prey since one would hope that their friends and allies would back them up when a heavily armed mercenary is gunning for them. So the question is: Who should be allowed to defend the hunted? Everyone in the area could simply join the fray, though that would add some complications of its own. A small group of friends could defend the prey, but that also takes away from the feeling of the game by limited who could be involved. All and all, its a tough choice to make.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
