			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Should victims be able to attack their bounty hunter or should they only be able to attack in self-defense (Bounty Hunter must make first attack as per rules of a challenger of a duel)? 
<br />
Of course victims should be able to attack their bounty hunters,...if they know they are THEIR bounty hunter. This assumes that the victim has sources of information to tell him he has a bounty on his head(ie. high enough faction rating with a well informed faction). This would assume the bounty hunter has interacted with npcs or in game sources to receive his bounty, which in turn would alert the victim pc to the bounty on his head. Otherwise the victim would just be pking to attack without first being attacked. 
<br />
I agree with Ventti entirely that a good bounty hunter would rely on best opportunity to attack & would prolly have access to the best toys with which to carry out his attack, but patience & remaining 'unobserved' would be his best strategies to a successful bounty.
<br />
Should victims know who their bounty hunter is?
<br />
See above,..If their sources are good enough,..or the hunter is stupid enough to tip off an observant victim pc,...sure.
<br />
What would you like to see in the Bounty Hunter system?
<br />
I guess, a system of both npc 'quest' bounty's, and faction based bountys. It would be nice if the bounty hunter was given a certain pk privaledge, being a class that is by nature, a gun for hire. Perhaps they would be the only pkers in the game, and only be able to pk once a bounty has been accepted by the hunter. The bountys that a hunter accepts and collects on, should of course, affect his faction rating with a victims faction to a certain extent as well, assuming it wasnt the victims own faction that put out the bounty on him....
<br />
It would also be nice to have a criminal tag for people who commit crimes against factions. ie. I have been witnessed killing storm troopers, I now have Imperial Criminal faction. Imperial bounty hunters (or any hunters that want Imperial faction) may then gain access to Imperial criminal files & perhaps gain more bounty for pcs with greater Imperial Criminal faction. This would also necessitate the need for unobserved criminal activities,...If you kill a storm trooper in a dark alley & get away unseen, you should NOT get Imperial Criminal faction,...That's realism & that is what will differentiate a GOOD game from...something else. 
<br />
What do you think would cause problems in the Bounty Hunter system?
<br />
Giving bountys to multiple hunters at the same time. This would create camping npcs for bounty, which nobody wants.
<br />
Conversely giving multiple hunters bountys for criminal pcs would be a great opportunity for a few hunters to group & perhaps share in a bounty. This would also mean as soon as a pc criminal has his bounty cashed in(ie. in the dead books), his bounty(but perhaps not his criminal faction) would have to be cleared.
<br />
Problem with this would be people committing crimes & having their noobie bounty hunter collecting bounty on their criminal character.
<br />
What do you think would cause problems in the Bounty Hunter system?
<br />
Not being able to be anonymous as a hunter,..(Hrmmm,..why has that 50th level bounty hunter been watching our party all night?...) 
<br />
If no one commits any crimes,..?
<br />
If EVERYONE is a bounty hunter?</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
